`crates/ctx-scan` is the ctx-scan crate root: a binary + library that walks a directory tree, maintains a hash-based `.context/` summary mirror, and exposes scan/check/prune/update plus a stop-hook mode via both CLI and library entry points. Depending on it gets you git-independent staleness detection, orphan cleanup, and a `--contract`-documented CLI surface, all covered end-to-end by the sibling test suite.

`src/` is the implementation: the `Staleness` pipeline (hash.rs → staleness.rs → runner.rs → render.rs), the walker/reconcile scope-consistency requirement, the `cpath` layout contract shared externally with `ctx-summarize`, and the CLI/runner/contract split. `tests/` is the hermetic, end-to-end verification of that pipeline using `FakeFs`/`StubAgent`, independently re-asserting lifecycle facts (`.ctxignore` seeding, hash/summary drift, no-model-call guarantees during prune/reconcile) that `src/` implements but doesn't itself test.

The two subtrees share one invariant surface: any new staleness category or change to what counts as "stale"/"orphaned" must be threaded through `src/`'s four pipeline files *and* reflected in `tests/`'s scan.rs/stop_hook.rs/reconcile.rs, or the two will silently diverge. Only the regeneration path (`scan_run`/`update_run`) ever constructs an `Agent`; everything else, in both implementation and tests, is filesystem-only.

No intent.md exists for this directory, so no divergence can be assessed.